comments.body:
I'm not sure that I understand what you're referring to as a callback. Maybe my edit wasn't super clear. I'm imagining something like this:

```go
ctx := &types.SystemContext{
  DockerRegistryUserAgent: cversion.UserAgent("skopeo/"+version.Version),
}
```


```go
// containers/image/version/version.go
func UserAgent(base string) string {
  ua := "containers-image/"+Version
  if base == "" {
    return ua
  }
  return fmt.Sprintf("%s %s", base, ua)
}
```

docker/docker does something similar in https://github.com/moby/moby/blob/master/pkg/useragent/useragent.go

And https://github.com/moby/moby/blob/46cdcd206c56172b95ba5c77b827a722dab426c5/dockerversion/useragent.go#L18 + https://github.com/moby/moby/blob/46cdcd206c56172b95ba5c77b827a722dab426c5/api/server/server.go#L132

(Which callers could also use, if they really wanted to pretend to be docker...)

It just seems simpler to have an option for "set the user-agent to this string" and then some accessory helpers for producing that string than to have a bunch of options for different string-assembling behavior.

> (It is possible that the User-Agent value chance could break some users, but those users can, in the short-term, revert to an older version and long-term we would like the servers to adjust instead of documenting a work-around that every user has to manually apply. And if we had to have an user override for this long-term, a file like registries.conf would make more sense than a CLI flag.)

Re-reading this, I _think_ I might understand what you're getting at -- you're thinking of this from the perspective of twiddling a string in a config file vs me thinking of this from the perspective of the golang API? Sorry for all this back and forth, I am not very familiar with the containers/image stuff, so I'm coming from a place of ignorance.
